<dl id="n09065c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n09" href="#n09065c">N09 (VI.B.1)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n09all.htm#n09065c"> 65(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> skygrey <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n09065c"><li>FW 475.31 </li><li><a href="../../flex/rA/lexrA.htm#n09065c">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/rA/l39rA.htm#n09065c">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n09065c">MS BL 47482b-63</ms> </li><li>JJA 58:005 <a name="rA1d" href="../../FF/fdra/rda.htm#rA1d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/r/rA1d.htm#n09065c">Draft: III&sect;3A.1</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Les premiers mots que les enfants chinois apprennent &agrave; lire dans le fameux Livre des Mille Caract&egrave;res sont: &ldquo;Le bleu est la couleur du ciel, le jaune est la couleur de la terre.&rdquo; La premi&egrave;re de ces propositions serait admise dans toutes les parties du monde, l&agrave; m&ecirc;me o&ugrave; <mark>le ciel est le plus souvent gris</mark>. <br><font color="green">[The first words that Chinese children learn to read in the famous Book of a Thousand Characters are: &ldquo;Blue is the colour of the sky, yellow is the colour of the earth&rdquo;. The first of these propositions would be accepted in all parts of the world, even those where the sky is more often grey.]</font> <small> L&eacute;on Metchnikoff, <a name="LMCG" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#LMCG"><cite title="source">La Civilisation et les grands fleuves Historiques</cite></a> (1889) 344 footnote</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
